Boil a large #pot{} of water with @salt{1/4%tsp} and pre-heat your #oven{} to 180 degrees. Peel the @sweet potato{1} and chop into roughly 2cm cubes. Separate the @broccoli{1} florets from the stalk (you can also peel, chop and cook the stalk!) and peel and finely chop the @garlic clove{2}.

Add the broccoli to a #baking tray{} along with the garlic, @oil{2%tbsp}, @salt{1/2%tsp} and a good grind of @black pepper{} and pop in the oven to cook for ~{20-25%mins}.

Boil the sweet potato for around ~{10-15%mins} or until soft. Lift the potatoes from the water once done and keep the water for the sauce.

Meanwhile, sandwich the @British chicken breasts{2} between two sheets of #clingfilm{}. Whack the chicken with a #rolling pin{} or the base of a #saucepan{} until they are just under 1cm thick.

Add @olive oil{1%tbsp} to a #non-stick frying pan{} on medium high heat. Season both sides of the chicken with a good pinch of @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}. Cook the chicken ~{5%mins} on each side, or until cooked through.

> The chicken is cooked when it is no longer pink in the middle.

Once cooked, keep it warm in the oven.

> Do not wash up your pan as we'll use it to make your sauce tastier later.

Once the potatoes are cooked and removed from the water. Mash them with a good pinch of @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch} and stir through @butter{1%tbsp}(if you have some).

== Peppercorn Sauce ==

To make your sauce, put your used pan back on medium-high heat. Once it gets hot add @water{300%ml} of the water from the sweet potato pot and stir in the @chicken stock pot{1/2}. Once the sauce reduces by half, take it from the heat and let it cool for ~{2%mins}. Stir through the @sour cream{1/2}.

> If you want to spice up your sauce, crush the @black peppercorns{1/4%tsp} in a #pestle and mortar{}. If you don't have a pestle and mortar you can put them in clingfilm and whack them with a pan. Add the crushed peppercorns to your sauce at the same time as the stock.

Slice the chicken and serve everything straight away with your hot sauce. YUM!